Defines `Staleness`, the shared report type consumed by `--check`, `--update`, and the Stop hook to describe what's out of sync between source and summaries.

It's a plain data struct with five `Vec<String>` fields, each populated by a different subsystem: `stale_dirs`/`changed_files` from hash-diffing (deepest-first ordering for `stale_dirs` matters to callers doing bottom-up regeneration), `orphan_leaves` for leaves whose source vanished, `missing_artifacts` for expected-but-absent files on disk (a gap the hash tree alone can't detect, since it only hashes source — see audit finding #11 referenced in the doc comment), and `orphan_artifacts` for present-but-unexpected derived files (populated by `crate::reconcile`), explicitly excluding anything already in `orphan_leaves` to avoid double-counting.

Two `const fn` predicates matter to callers: `is_fresh()` requires all five vecs empty. `needs_regeneration()` is a narrower check — true only if `stale_dirs`, `changed_files`, or `orphan_leaves` are non-empty — distinguishing "must invoke the model to regenerate summaries" from "purely filesystem pruning needed" (i.e., only `missing_artifacts`/`orphan_artifacts` populated). Callers branching on "should I call the LLM" must use `needs_regeneration()`, not `!is_fresh()`, or they'll invoke generation unnecessarily for pure-orphan cases.